message.content:
We need to “derive” the gross profit (that is, the sum of the profit figures from every sale transaction) from the data. (Note that all non‐sale transactions – such as purchase, expense, depreciation, interest, etc. – do not affect “gross profit” as defined here because the profit column is provided only on sale rows.) 

For example, in the provided dataset each “Sale” row has a “profit” value in its last column. Our job is to add these up.

Below is one way to “reason” through the solution:

1. First we filter the transactions for sales – that is, rows where the “type” field is “Sale.”
2. Then for each sale row we extract the “profit” number (the last field). For instance, one sale row shows a profit of 33,170.71, another shows 27,593.55, then 1,943.51, etc.
3. Adding (summing) all of these profit amounts gives our final “gross profit” figure.
